nts about the Reformation and its connection to the (Eastern) Orthodox), but disagree with the doctrinal direction that the Medieval Roman Church took, which is still effective today. Lutherans are confessionally liturgical in worship - although that is changing in some areas. But the liturgical continuity of the historic &quot;mass&quot; (don't think of this in Roman Catholic terms) is something to be treasured, linking the saints of all ages in worship. We have 2 1/2 sacraments (Baptism, Lord's Supper, Confession/absolution), because our definition of sacraments is different than Roman Catholicism.<br>
<br>
At the same time, we are products of the Reformation, but do not fit into &quot;Protestant&quot; label, which is essentially Calvinism/Arminianism, which Lutherans reject both position, regarding predestination (Calvinism) and &quot;decision thhology&quot; (Arminianism) and the lower view of the sacraments.<br>
<br>
So, as I mention in my intro - Christian by faith, Lutheran by confession. <p>In Christ,<br>
<br>
filo<br>
