I'm not familiar with Lutheran churches.  But from what I've seen, I feel as though most churches are nothing like the New Testament church.  I think if we were to go back and be like the New Testament church, then we would not have church buildings and believers would meet together in people's homes.  It would be much more informal than the stiff, formal churches most churches I've seen tend to be - where there is one person in charge (or a few) doing all the work while the majority just follows along, more out of tradition than any kind of conviction.  We either feel nothing from the sermon given and no desire to change anything about ourselves, for perhaps the message of the sermon didn't even challenge us, or those who feel moved by the message don't follow through because they lack the accountability you would find meeting with just a few believers in someone's house.  The church buildings set themselves up too easily for people to walk in and out of the doors every week, never getting to know anyone, never feeling welcomed or a part of the congregation, for sometimes the loneliest place on earth to be is in a packed church sanctuary.  People who talk about the love of Christ yet don't show it to those within the church walls.  And certainly if the church is of a considerable size, the church leaders can not form close bonds with everyone who comes in through the doors.<br>
<br>
Yet we formalize a church service and call it worship, all the while, the Bible gives us a very different definition of worship, one which many people who go to a church don't demonstrate.  Thus so many people in the world don't know what makes Christians different than them other than we're tolerant enough to sing a few really old songs, often to a piano or organ designed for relaxing us to sleep and sit through an often boring lecture aka a sermon.  As most people don't want to be preached at (as the word has so many negative connotations).<br>
<br>
And how many people have been hurt by people claiming to be Christians?  (Not knowing if they truly were for as the Bible says, many will call Jesus Lord whom He does not know.)  For those who tried church to find nothing but loneliness, feeling Christians are hypocritical to be talking about love and yet not showing it.  Or there are other similar things, some more severe even.  Periodically my church will do a random acts of kindness thing and one night on Halloween, some were passing out cans of pop to people.  One guy handed a can to a guy and as he walked away, the guy who gave the can said, &quot;Just to show you the love of Jesus in a practical way.&quot;  The man walked back and gave back the can, saying something like, &quot;I don't want anything to do with your Jesus.&quot;  And one must wonder why a person would have such a hatred towards the one person in this world who loved Him the most.  Do our words or actions push people away from Christ?  Or do our lack of words and actions push them away.<br>
<br>
Some might argue that that's not fair, we're not responsible for people we've not met.  But when was the last time we looked around our church building to see someone sitting by themself and went out of our way to do more than shake their hand and mumble a hello if we even did that much?  No, I feel our churches today are nothing like the New Testament church.  We have isolated ourselves from people.  So many people go to church because it's how they were brought up - it's tradition.  We hold to our traditions so much that we ignore the fact that the heart of Christ is bleeding out and crying because His love isn't being shared.  It's so often not shared within our church walls, how can we hope to share it with the lost?  Whether we like it or not, Christians are put under a microscope by the lost, they pick up on things that perhaps we don't pick up on ourselves - because we're not questioning God's existence.  And too often we act like His spoiled children, rebellious and pushing our Father's limits to see how much we can get away with by not doing what He commands.  Because to do what He wants from us often means to take us out of our comfort zone.  It means we can't be lazy.  It means doing things our sinful nature wants to avoid.<br>
<br>
And this is a problem that extends to all kinds of churches be it catholic or protestant or whatever.  We live with such freedoms and materialism that we become too comfortable with our lives that we aren't self-sacrificing as Christ commands.  It's harder to die to yourself to let Christ live in you when you're holding onto the things of this world.  And I feel that in our churches today, we're full of people like this.  In my own church, for example, I get annoyed when the pastors tell the congregation something like, &quot;Don't worry, we'll get out early enough so you can watch the game on tv.&quot;  And even when there's not a big game coming on after the service, they apologize if they don't dismiss the congregation until five or ten minutes after the time service is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>suppose</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to be over.<br>
<br>
And I want to scream, &quot;Where's our passion?!&quot;  Is church just an inconveinance to us?  I hate to say that many times church attendance is down if there's a game going on during church service.  Who or what do we worship?  Who or what takes first priority in our lives?  If it's God, then we go to church, even if it is a miserable place because even if everyone else gives a cold shoulder, we know we can be the one to start going out and meeting people we don't know and making them feel welcome.  Because if we want to see change, we have to bring about change.  We have to be the ones to start.  But nobody likes going against the flow and being different.  For if everyone rejects us, it hurts deeply, and it's easy to forget how pleased God is with us, even when our brothers and sisters might not be.  Before we can reach the lost, we have to reach each other.<br>
<br>
So, wow, that was long.  But back to my point, I don't feel churches today are anything like the New Testament church.  I think it was a lot less formal and extremely informal.  IMO, the ones who formalized it were the Jews who held to their traditional Jewish beliefs and believed there had to be a set order to things.  While God is almighty and worthy of our deepest respect and honor and worship, He has chosen to call us His children rather than His servants and chosen to come in the form of a human - Jesus, to relate even more informally with us, and He has said that marriage is a physical representation of the spiritual love and closeness He desires from us.  And I feel churches today are a poor reflection of the intimacy He desires with us.<br>
<br>
Sorry to go so long, I'll jump down off my soap box now. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>**********************************************<br>
